# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vector-search
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:vector-search/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The **curse of dimensionality** refers to various phenomena that arise when analyzing and organizing data in high-dimensional spaces that do not occur in low-dimensional settings such as the three-dimensional physical space of everyday experience.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Bellman when considering problems in dynamic programming.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The curse generally refers to issues that arise when the number of datapoints is small (in a suitably defined sense) relative to the intrinsic dimension of the data.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Dimensionally cursed phenomena occur in domains such as numerical analysis, sampling, combinatorics, machine learning, data mining and databases.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The common theme of these problems is that when the dimensionality increases, the volume of the space increases so fast that the available data becomes sparse.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In order to obtain a reliable result, the amount of data needed often grows exponentially with the dimensionality.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Also, organizing and searching data often relies on detecting areas where objects form groups with similar properties; in high dimensional data, however, all objects appear to be sparse and dissimilar in many ways, which prevents common data organization strategies from being efficient.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In some problems, each variable can take one of several discrete values, or the range of possible values is divided to give a finite number of possibilities.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Taking the variables together, a huge number of combinations of values must be considered.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This effect is also known as the combinatorial explosion.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Even in the simplest case of d binary variables, the number of possible combinations already is $2^{d}$ , exponential in the dimensionality.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Naively, each additional dimension doubles the effort needed to try all combinations.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] There is an exponential increase in volume associated with adding extra dimensions to a mathematical space.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In general, with a spacing distance of 10−*n* the 10-dimensional hypercube appears to be a factor of 10*n*(10−1) = [(10*n*)10/(10*n*)] "larger" than the 1-dimensional hypercube, which is the unit interval.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In the above example *n* = 2: when using a sampling distance of 0.01 the 10-dimensional hypercube appears to be 1018 "larger" than the unit interval.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This effect is a combination of the combinatorics problems above and the distance function problems explained below.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] When solving dynamic optimization problems by numerical backward induction, the objective function must be evaluated for each combination of values in a discretized state space.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This is a significant obstacle when the dimension of the "state variable" is large.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In an abstract sense, as the number of features or dimensions grows, the amount of data we need to generalize accurately grows exponentially.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] A typical rule of thumb is that there should be at least 5 training examples for each dimension in the representation.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In machine learning and insofar as predictive performance is concerned, the *curse of dimensionality* is used interchangeably with the *peaking phenomenon*, which is also known as *Hughes phenomenon*.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In other words, both the size of additional features and their (relative) cumulative discriminatory effect are important in observing a decrease or increase in the average predictive power.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In metric learning, higher dimensions can sometimes allow a model to achieve better performance.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] After normalizing embeddings to the surface of a hypersphere, FaceNet achieves the best performance using 128 dimensions as opposed to 64, 256, or 512 dimensions in one ablation study.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] A loss function for unitary-invariant dissimilarity between word embeddings was found to be minimized in high dimensions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In data mining, the curse of dimensionality refers to a data set with too many features.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Consider the first table, which depicts 200 individuals and 2000 genes (features) with a 1 or 0 denoting whether or not they have a genetic mutation in that gene.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] A data mining application to this data set may be finding the correlation between specific genetic mutations and creating a classification algorithm such as a decision tree to determine whether an individual has cancer or not.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] A common practice of data mining in this domain would be to create association rules between genetic mutations that lead to the development of cancers.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] To do this, one would have to loop through each genetic mutation of each individual and find other genetic mutations that occur over a desired threshold and create pairs.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] They would start with pairs of two, then three, then four until they result in an empty set of pairs.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The complexity of this algorithm can lead to calculating all permutations of gene pairs for each individual or row.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Given the formula for calculating the permutations of n items with a group size of r is: ${\frac {n!}{(n-r)!}}$ , calculating the number of three pair permutations of any given individual would be 7988004000 different pairs of genes to evaluate for each individual.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The number of pairs created will grow by an order of factorial as the size of the pairs increase.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The growth is depicted in the permutation table (see right).
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] As we can see from the permutation table above, one of the major problems data miners face regarding the curse of dimensionality is that the space of possible parameter values grows exponentially or factorially as the number of features in the data set grows.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This problem critically affects both computational time and space when searching for associations or optimal features to consider.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Another problem data miners may face when dealing with too many features is that the number of false predictions or classifications tends to increase as the number of features grows in the data set.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In terms of the classification problem discussed above, keeping every data point could lead to a higher number of false positives and false negatives in the model.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This may seem counterintuitive, but consider the genetic mutation table from above, depicting all genetic mutations for each individual.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Each genetic mutation, whether they correlate with cancer or not, will have some input or weight in the model that guides the decision-making process of the algorithm.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] There may be mutations that are outliers or ones that dominate the overall distribution of genetic mutations when in fact they do not correlate with cancer.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] These features may be working against one's model, making it more difficult to obtain optimal results.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This problem is up to the data miner to solve, and there is no universal solution.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The first step any data miner should take is to explore the data, in an attempt to gain an understanding of how it can be used to solve the problem.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] One must first understand what the data means, and what they are trying to discover before they can decide if anything must be removed from the data set.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Then they can create or use a feature selection or dimensionality reduction algorithm to remove samples or features from the data set if they deem it necessary.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] One example of such methods is the interquartile range method, used to remove outliers in a data set by calculating the standard deviation of a feature or occurrence.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] When a measure such as a Euclidean distance is defined using many coordinates, there is little difference in the distances between different pairs of points.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] As the dimension d of the space increases, the hypersphere becomes an insignificant volume relative to that of the hypercube.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Furthermore, the distance between the center and the corners is $r{\sqrt {d}}$ , which increases without bound for fixed r.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In this sense when points are uniformly generated in a high-dimensional hypercube, almost all points are much farther than r units away from the center.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In high dimensions, the volume of the *d*-dimensional unit hypercube (with coordinates of the vertices $\pm 1$ ) is concentrated near a sphere with the radius ${\sqrt {d}}/{\sqrt {3}}$ for large dimension *d*.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Therefore, the squared distance from the origin, ${\textstyle r^{2}=\sum _{i}x_{i}^{2}}$ has the average value *d*/3 and variance 4*d*/45.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] For large *d*, distribution of $r^{2}/d$ is close to the normal distribution with the mean 1/3 and the standard deviation $2/{\sqrt {45d}}$ according to the central limit theorem.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Thus, when uniformly generating points in high dimensions, both the "middle" of the hypercube, and the corners are empty, and all the volume is concentrated near the surface of a sphere of "intermediate" radius ${\textstyle {\sqrt {d/3}}}$ .
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This also helps to understand the chi-squared distribution.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Indeed, the (non-central) chi-squared distribution associated to a random point in the interval [-1, 1] is the same as the distribution of the length-squared of a random point in the *d*-cube.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] By the law of large numbers, this distribution concentrates itself in a narrow band around *d* times the standard deviation squared (σ2) of the original derivation.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This illuminates the chi-squared distribution and also illustrates that most of the volume of the *d*-cube concentrates near the boundary of a sphere of radius $\sigma {\sqrt {d}}$ .
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] A further development of this phenomenon is as follows.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Any fixed distribution on the real numbers induces a product distribution on points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This is often cited as distance functions losing their usefulness (for the nearest-neighbor criterion in feature-comparison algorithms, for example) in high dimensions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] However, recent research has shown this to only hold in the artificial scenario when the one-dimensional distributions $\mathbb {R}$ are independent and identically distributed.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] When attributes are correlated, data can become easier and provide higher distance contrast and the signal-to-noise ratio was found to play an important role, thus feature selection should be used.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] More recently, it has been suggested that there may be a conceptual flaw in the argument that contrast-loss creates a curse in high dimensions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Machine learning can be understood as the problem of assigning instances to their respective generative process of origin, with class labels acting as symbolic representations of individual generative processes.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The curse's derivation assumes all instances are independent, identical outcomes of a single high dimensional generative process.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] If there is only one generative process, there would exist only one (naturally occurring) class and machine learning would be conceptually ill-defined in both high and low dimensions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Thus, the traditional argument that contrast-loss creates a curse, may be fundamentally inappropriate.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In addition, it has been shown that when the generative model is modified to accommodate multiple generative processes, contrast-loss can morph from a curse to a blessing, as it ensures that the nearest-neighbor of an instance is almost-surely its most closely related instance.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] From this perspective, contrast-loss makes high dimensional distances especially meaningful and not especially non-meaningful as is often argued.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The effect complicates nearest neighbor search in high dimensional space.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] It is not possible to quickly reject candidates by using the difference in one coordinate as a lower bound for a distance based on all the dimensions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] However, it has recently been observed that the mere number of dimensions does not necessarily result in difficulties, since *relevant* additional dimensions can also increase the contrast.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In addition, for the resulting ranking it remains useful to discern close and far neighbors.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Irrelevant ("noise") dimensions, however, reduce the contrast in the manner described above.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In time series analysis, where the data are inherently high-dimensional, distance functions also work reliably as long as the signal-to-noise ratio is high enough.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Another effect of high dimensionality on distance functions concerns *k*-nearest neighbor (*k*-NN) graphs constructed from a data set using a distance function.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] As the dimension increases, the indegree distribution of the *k*-NN digraph becomes skewed with a peak on the right because of the emergence of a disproportionate number of **hubs**, that is, data-points that appear in many more *k*-NN lists of other data-points than the average.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This phenomenon can have a considerable impact on various techniques for classification (including the *k*-NN classifier), semi-supervised learning, and clustering, and it also affects information retrieval.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Hubness: certain objects occur more frequently in neighbor lists than others.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Many of the analyzed specialized methods tackle one or another of these problems, but there remain many open research questions.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Despite the expected "curse of dimensionality" difficulties, common-sense heuristics based on the most straightforward methods "can yield results which are almost surely optimal" for high-dimensional problems.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The term "blessing of dimensionality" was introduced in the late 1990s.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Donoho in his "Millennium manifesto" explained why he thinks the "blessing of dimensionality" will form a basis of future data mining.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] The effects of the blessing of dimensionality were discovered in many applications and found their foundation in the concentration of measure phenomena.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] One example of the blessing of dimensionality phenomenon is linear separability of a random point from a large finite random set with high probability even if this set is exponentially large: the number of elements in this random set can grow exponentially with dimension.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] Moreover, this linear functional can be selected in the form of the simplest linear Fisher discriminant.
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This separability theorem was proven for a wide class of probability distributions: general uniformly log-concave distributions, product distributions in a cube and many other families (reviewed recently in ).
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] This property significantly simplifies the expected geometry of data and indexing of high-dimensional data (blessing), but, at the same time, it makes the similarity search in high dimensions difficult and even useless (curse).
[src:vector-search/curse-of-dimensionality] In particular for unsupervised data analysis this effect is known as swamping.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] In computer science, **locality-sensitive hashing** (**LSH**) is a fuzzy hashing technique that hashes similar input items into the same "buckets" with high probability.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] The number of buckets is much smaller than the universe of possible input items.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since similar items end up in the same buckets, this technique can be used for data clustering and nearest neighbor search.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] It differs from conventional hashing techniques in that hash collisions are maximized, not minimized.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively, the technique can be seen as a way to reduce the dimensionality of high-dimensional data; high-dimensional input items can be reduced to low-dimensional versions while preserving relative distances between items.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Hashing-based approximate nearest-neighbor search algorithms generally use one of two main categories of hashing methods: either data-independent methods, such as locality-sensitive hashing (LSH); or data-dependent methods, such as locality-preserving hashing (LPH).
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Locality-preserving hashing was initially devised as a way to facilitate data pipelining in implementations of massively parallel algorithms that use randomized routing and universal hashing to reduce memory contention and network congestion.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] if it satisfies the following condition.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively it is possible to define an LSH family on a universe of items U endowed with a similarity function $\phi \colon U\times U\to [0,1]$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] In this setting, a LSH scheme is a family of hash functions H coupled with a probability distribution D over H such that a function $h\in H$ chosen according to D satisfies $Pr[h(a)=h(b)]=\phi (a,b)$ for each $a,b\in U$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a $(d_{1},d_{2},p_{1},p_{2})$ -sensitive family ${\mathcal {F}}$ , we can construct new families ${\mathcal {G}}$ by either the AND-construction or OR-construction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an AND-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an OR-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] We then say that for a hash function $g\in {\mathcal {G}}$ , $g(x)=g(y)$ if and only if $h_{i}(x)=h_{i}(y)$ for one or more values of i.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the easiest ways to construct an LSH family is by bit sampling.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] This approach works for the Hamming distance over d-dimensional vectors $\{0,1\}^{d}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Here, the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ of hash functions is simply the family of all the projections of points on one of the d coordinates, i.e., ${\mathcal {F}}=\{h\colon \{0,1\}^{d}\to \{0,1\}\mid h(x)=x_{i}{\text{ for some }}i\in \{1,\ldots ,d\}\}$ , where $x_{i}$ is the i th coordinate of x .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] A random function h from ${\mathcal {F}}$ simply selects a random bit from the input point.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, any two vectors $x,y$ with Hamming distance at most R collide under a random h with probability at least $P_{1}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Any $x,y$ with Hamming distance at least $cR$ collide with probability at most $P_{2}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Suppose U is composed of subsets of some ground set of enumerable items S and the similarity function of interest is the Jaccard index J.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] If π is a permutation on the indices of S, for $A\subseteq S$ let $h(A)=\min _{a\in A}\{\pi (a)\}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each possible choice of π defines a single hash function h mapping input sets to elements of S.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Define the function family H to be the set of all such functions and let D be the uniform distribution.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given two sets $A,B\subseteq S$ the event that $h(A)=h(B)$ corresponds exactly to the event that the minimizer of π over $A\cup B$ lies inside $A\cap B$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] As h was chosen uniformly at random, $Pr[h(A)=h(B)]=J(A,B)\,$ and $(H,D)\,$ define an LSH scheme for the Jaccard index.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because the symmetric group on n elements has size n!, choosing a truly random permutation from the full symmetric group is infeasible for even moderately sized n.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because of this fact, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent" — a permutation family for which each element of the domain has equal probability of being the minimum under a randomly chosen π.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] It has been established that a min-wise independent family of permutations is at least of size $\operatorname {lcm} \{\,1,2,\ldots ,n\,\}\geq e^{n-o(n)}$ , and that this bound is tight.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because min-wise independent families are too big for practical applications, two variant notions of min-wise independence are introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most k.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Approximate min-wise independence differs from the property by at most a fixed ε.
