[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] The basic idea of this technique is to choose a random hyperplane (defined by a normal unit vector r) at the outset and use the hyperplane to hash input vectors.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given an input vector v and a hyperplane defined by r, we let $h(v)=\operatorname {sgn}(v\cdot r)$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, $h(v)=\pm 1$ depending on which side of the hyperplane v lies.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] This way, each possible choice of a random hyperplane r can be interpreted as a hash function $h(v)$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since the ratio between ${\frac {\theta (u,v)}{\pi }}$ and $1-\cos(\theta (u,v))$ is at least 0.439 when $\theta (u,v)\in [0,\pi ]$ , the probability of two vectors being on different sides of the random hyperplane is approximately proportional to the cosine distance between them.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] The hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}):{\mathcal {R}}^{d}\to {\mathcal {N}}$ maps a d-dimensional vector ${\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}$ onto the set of integers.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each hash function in the family is indexed by a choice of random $\mathbf {a}$ and b where $\mathbf {a}$ is a d-dimensional vector with entries chosen independently from a stable distribution and b is a real number chosen uniformly from the range [0,r].
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] For a fixed $\mathbf {a} ,b$ the hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}$ is given by $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }})=\left\lfloor {\frac {\mathbf {a} \cdot {\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}+b}{r}}\right\rfloor$ .
