[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the main applications of LSH is to provide a method for efficient approximate nearest neighbor search algorithms.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Consider an LSH family ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm has two main parameters: the width parameter k and the number of hash tables L.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the first step, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is obtained by concatenating k functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ , i.e., $g(p)=[h_{1}(p),\ldots ,h_{k}(p)]$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] In other words, a random hash function g is obtained by concatenating k randomly chosen hash functions from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm then constructs L hash tables, each corresponding to a different randomly chosen hash function g.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the preprocessing step we hash all n d-dimensional points from the data set S into each of the L hash tables.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given that the resulting hash tables have only n non-zero entries, one can reduce the amount of memory used per each hash table to $O(n)$ using standard hash functions.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a query point q, the algorithm iterates over the L hash functions g.
[src:vector-search/locality-sensitive-hashing] For each g considered, it retrieves the data points that are hashed into the same bucket as q.
