[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:vector-search/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
